        "type": "tool_result",
        "content": "1\t# Core Concept Comparison\n2\t\n3\tThis document compares Relative Meta-Logic (RML) with the systems named in\n4\t[issue #22](https://github.com/link-foundation/relative-meta-logic/issues/22)\n5\tby core logical and metatheoretic concepts. Product and workflow capabilities\n6\tare compared separately in [FEATURE-COMPARISION.md](./FEATURE-COMPARISION.md).\n7\t\n8\tThe goal is positioning, not a claim that every system has the same design\n9\ttarget. Several entries are logical frameworks, some are full proof assistants,\n10\tsome are libraries inside a host prover, and Pecan is a domain-specific\n11\tautomated prover.\n12\t\n13\t## Legend\n14\t\n15\t| Mark | Meaning |\n16\t|------|---------|\n17\t| Yes | First-class or central capability |\n18\t| Part | Partial, prototype, limited, indirect, or available by encoding |\n19\t| Host | Inherited from the host proof assistant rather than implemented by the project itself |\n20\t| Theory | Theoretical framework rather than a standalone product implementation |\n21\t| N/A | Not applicable to the system's role |\n22\t| No | No evidence of support or outside the system's design goal |\n23\t\n24\t## Systems\n25\t\n26\t| System | Primary role |\n27\t|--------|--------------|\n28\t| RML | Link-based probabilistic and many-valued meta-logic with JS and Rust implementations |\n29\t| Twelf | LF implementation with type checking, logic programming, and metatheorem checking |\n30\t| Edinburgh LF | Dependently typed logical framework for representing deductive systems |\n31\t| HELF | Haskell implementation of an LF/Twelf subset for parsing and type checking `.elf` files |\n32\t| Isabelle | Generic interactive theorem prover, especially Isabelle/Pure and Isabelle/HOL |\n33\t| Coq/Rocq | Interactive theorem prover based on the Calculus of Inductive Constructions |\n34\t| Lean | Interactive theorem prover and programming language based on dependent type theory |\n35\t| Foundation | Lean 4 library formalizing mathematical logic |\n36\t| AFP | Isabelle Archive of Formal Proofs, a checked archive of Isabelle developments |\n37\t| Abella | Interactive prover for lambda-tree syntax and two-level logic reasoning |\n38\t| lambda Prolog | Higher-order hereditary Harrop logic programming language |\n39\t| Pecan | Automated theorem prover for automatic sequences and Buchi automata |\n40\t\n41\t## Foundations and Representation\n42\t\n43\t| Core concept | RML | Twelf | Edinburgh LF | HELF | Isabelle | Coq/Rocq | Lean | Foundation | AFP | Abella | lambda Prolog | Pecan |\n44\t|--------------|-----|-------|--------------|------|----------|----------|------|------------|-----|--------|---------------|-------|\n45\t| General meta-logic for object logics | Yes: link substrate can encode many logics | Yes | Yes | Part | Yes: Pure framework | Part: can encode logics in CIC | Part: can encode logics in DTT | Yes: logic formalizations in Lean | Host: Isabelle entries | Yes | Part: specification language | No |\n46\t| Uniform representation of syntax and judgments | Yes: links | Yes: LF terms | Yes: LF terms | Yes: LF terms | Part: Pure/HOL terms | Yes: CIC terms | Yes: dependent terms | Host | Host | Yes: two-level terms | Yes: lambda terms | Part: formulas and automata |\n47\t| One syntactic category for terms/propositions/proofs | Part: links are uniform; proof terms are prototype only | Yes in LF style | Yes in LF style | Yes in LF subset | Part: terms/propositions distinct in HOL layer | Yes | Yes | Host | Host | Part | Part | No |\n48\t| Explicit object-language encodings | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Part |\n49\t| Adequacy-oriented encodings | Part | Yes | Yes | Part | Yes by proof development | Yes by proof development | Yes by proof development | Host | Host | Yes | Part | No |\n50\t| Links or tuples as primitive notation | Yes | No | No | No | No | No | No | No | No | No | No | No |\n51\t| Named constants and declarations | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Host | Host | Yes | Yes | Yes |\n52\t| Definitions as first-class source entries | Yes | Yes | Theory | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Host | Host | Yes | Yes | Yes |\n53\t| Structural equality over expressions | Yes | Yes: type theory equality/convertibility | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Host | Host | Part | Part | Domain-specific equality |\n54\t| Numeric truth values in the core | Yes | No | No | No | No | No | No | No | No | No | No | Part: arithmetic domains |\n55\t| Configurable semantic range | Yes: `[0,1]` or `[-1,1]` | No | No | No | No | No | No | No | No | No | No | No |\n56\t| Configurable valence | Yes: unary, Boolean, N-valued, continuous | No | No | No | No | No | No | No | No | No | No | No |\n57\t| Self-reference accepted by default | Yes: midpoint/paradox-tolerant evaluation | No | No | No | No | No | No | Host constraints | Host constraints | Part: coinductive reasoning only | No | No |\n58\t| Circular definitions as ordinary data | Part | No | No | No | Guarded/fixed-point mechanisms | Guarded/termination rules | Guarded/termination rules | Host | Host | Coinductive predicates | Recursive programs with restrictions | Automata fixed points |\n59\t\n60\t## Type Theory and Binding\n61\t\n62\t| Core concept | RML | Twelf | Edinburgh LF | HELF | Isabelle | Coq/Rocq | Lean | Foundation | AFP | Abella | lambda Prolog | Pecan |\n63\t|--------------|-----|-------|--------------|------|----------|----------|------|------------|-----|--------|---------------|-------|\n64\t| Dependent types | Part: prototype type layer | Yes | Yes | Yes | No: HOL is simply typed; Pure is higher-order | Yes | Yes | Host | Host | No: simply typed reasoning/spec logics | No: polymorphic/simple typed | No |\n65\t| Dependent products / Pi-types | Part | Yes | Yes | Yes | Part: meta-level universal quantification | Yes | Yes | Host | Host | No | No | No |\n66\t| Lambda abstraction | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Host | Host | Yes | Yes | No |\n67\t| Function application | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Host | Host | Yes | Yes | No |\n68\t| Beta reduction | Part: beta for link lambdas | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Host | Host | Part | Yes | No |\n69\t| Definitional equality / conversion | Part | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Host | Host | Part | Part: beta conversion | No |\n70\t| Full normalization | No: evaluator is not a normalizer | Yes for LF canonical forms | Yes in theory | Part | Yes where defined by logic/tools | Yes | Yes | Host | Host | Part | Part | No |\n71\t| Universe hierarchy | Part: `(Type 0)`, `(Type 1)` | No: LF has kinds/types | No | No | No in HOL; object theories possible | Yes | Yes | Host | Host | No | No | No |\n72\t| Sorts / kinds | Part | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes: types/classes/logics | Yes | Yes | Host | Host | Yes: type declarations | Yes | Domain sorts |\n73\t| Type annotations | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Host | Host | Yes | Yes | Yes: domain declarations |\n74\t| Type inference | Part | Part: reconstruction | Theory | No reconstruction | Yes | Yes | Yes | Host | Host | Part | Yes | Part |\n75\t| Type checking | Part | Yes | Theory | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Host | Host | Yes | Yes | Yes: domain/formula checking |\n76\t| Higher-order abstract syntax | Part: encodable as links | Yes | Yes | Yes | Part | Part | Part | Host | Host | Yes | Yes | No |\n77\t| Lambda-tree syntax | Part | Yes/related | Yes/related | Yes/related | Encodable | Encodable | Encodable | Host | Host | Yes | Yes | No |\n78\t| Binding-aware substitution | Part | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes | Host | Host | Yes | Yes | No |\n79\t| Variable freshness support | Part | Part | Part | Part | Yes by libraries/packages | Yes by libraries/packages | Yes by libraries/packages | Host/libraries | Host/libraries | Yes: nabla/generic judgments | Part | No |\n80\t| Polymorphism | No dedicated system | Part | Part | Part | Yes | Yes | Yes | Host | Host | Schematic polymorphism | Yes | Domain-specific |"
