        "text": "This session is being continued from a previous conversation that ran out of context. The summary below covers the earlier portion of the conversation.\n\nSummary:\n1. Primary Request and Intent:\n   The user requested implementing Issue #29 — Interactive REPL for the Relative Meta-Logic (RML) project. The REPL must:\n   - Preserve `Env` state across user inputs (each line evaluates against persistent env)\n   - Print diagnostics inline (file:line:col error format)\n   - Support meta-commands: `:reset`, `:env`, `:load <file>`, `:save <file>` (plus `:help`, `:quit`/`:exit`)\n   - Provide best-effort tab-completion of declared symbols\n   - Be implemented in BOTH the JavaScript and Rust implementations as a `rml repl` subcommand\n   - Include tests covering state preservation and meta-commands\n   - Update existing PR #100 (draft) on `issue-29-9fcddd60fd98` branch\n   \n   Example LiNo session from issue:\n   ```\n   rml> (a: a is a)\n   rml> ((a = a) has probability 1)\n   rml> (? (a = a))\n   1\n   ```\n\n2. Key Technical Concepts:\n   - LiNo (Links Notation) — parenthesized expression syntax\n   - RML (Relative Meta-Logic) — link-based probabilistic many-valued logic\n   - Many-valued logics (Boolean, ternary, fuzzy, Belnap four-valued)\n   - Node.js `readline` for line-editing with completer\n   - ESM (ES Modules) circular dependency resolution / top-level await pitfalls\n   - Rust `catch_unwind` / `AssertUnwindSafe` for evaluator panic handling\n   - Persistent `Env` (terms, ops, types, lambdas, assign, symbol_prob)\n   - Structured diagnostics (E001-E006 error codes with source spans)\n\n3. Files and Code Sections:\n   - **`/tmp/gh-issue-solver-1777477811289/js/src/rml-links.mjs`** (1112 lines, modified)\n     - Modified `evaluate(code, options)` to accept existing Env: `const env = opts.env instanceof Env ? opts.env : new Env(opts.env || opts);`\n     - Replaced old CLI block with new `runCli()` async function supporting `repl` subcommand. Uses `new URL('./rml-repl.mjs', import.meta.url).href` for path resolution. Wrapped CLI invocation:\n       ```js\n       async function runCli() {\n         const arg = process.argv[2];\n         if (!arg) { console.error('Usage: rml <kb.lino>   |   rml repl'); process.exit(1); }\n         if (arg === 'repl') {\n           const replUrl = new URL('./rml-repl.mjs', import.meta.url).href;\n           const { runRepl } = await import(replUrl);\n           await runRepl();\n           return;\n         }\n         const text = fs.readFileSync(arg, 'utf8');\n         const { results, diagnostics } = evaluate(text, { file: arg });\n         /* ... print results and diagnostics ... */\n         if (diagnostics.length > 0) process.exit(1);\n       }\n       if (import.meta.url === `file://${process.argv[1]}`) {\n         runCli().catch(err => { console.error(err && err.stack ? err.stack : err); process.exit(1); });\n       }\n       ```\n\n   - **`/tmp/gh-issue-solver-1777477811289/js/src/rml-repl.mjs`** (NEW, ~245 lines)\n     - Exports: `Repl` class, `runRepl()`, `formatEnv()`, `makeCompleter()`, `envCompletionCandidates()`, `HELP_TEXT`\n     - `Repl` class methods: `reset()`, `evaluateSource(source, file)`, `feed(line)`, `_handleMeta(line)`, `_resolve(p)`\n     - Meta-commands handled: `:help`/`:?`, `:quit`/`:exit`, `:reset`, `:env`, `:load`, `:save`\n     - `runRepl()` uses `readline.createInterface` with `completer: makeCompleter(() => repl.env)`\n     - `formatEnv(env)` prints range/valence, terms, lambdas, types, assignments, user-set symbol priors\n\n   - **`/tmp/gh-issue-solver-1777477811289/rust/src/lib.rs`** (modified)\n     - Added `evaluate_with_env(text, file, env)` function (refactored body of `evaluate()`)\n     - `evaluate()` now wraps it: `let mut env = Env::new(options); evaluate_with_env(text, file, &mut env)`\n     - Loop changed from `eval_node(&form, &mut env)` to `eval_node(&form, env)` (env now `&mut Env` parameter)\n\n   - **`/tmp/gh-issue-solver-1777477811289/rust/src/repl.rs`** (NEW, ~360 lines)\n     - `pub struct Repl { pub env: Env, pub transcript: Vec<String>, env_options: EnvOptions, cwd: PathBuf }`\n     - `pub struct ReplStep { pub output: String, pub error: String, pub exit: bool }`\n     - Methods: `new()`, `reset()`, `evaluate_source(source, file) -> (String, String)`, `feed(line) -> ReplStep`, `handle_meta(line)`, `resolve(p)`, `completion_candidates(prefix) -> Vec<String>`\n     - `pub fn format_env(env: &Env) -> String`\n     - `pub fn run_repl(env_options, show_prompt, input, output, err_output)` driver\n     - Constants: `BUILTIN_KEYWORDS`, `META_COMMANDS`, `HELP_TEXT`\n     - 6 unit tests in `#[cfg(test)] mod tests`: `preserves_state_across_feeds`, `reset_clears_state`, `help_emits_help_text`, `unknown_meta_command_reports_error`, `quit_requests_exit`, `completion_offers_terms_after_declaration`, `completion_offers_meta_commands_for_colon_prefix`\n\n4. Errors and fixes:\n   - **`links-notation` package not found** when running JS CLI: Fixed by running `npm install` in `js/` directory.\n   \n   - **Exit code 13 (Unfinished Top-Level Await)** when running `node src/rml-links.mjs repl`: Caused by ESM circular dependency — `rml-repl.mjs` statically imports `evaluate, Env, formatDiagnostic` from `rml-links.mjs`, while `rml-links.mjs`'s CLI block was using top-level `await import('./rml-repl.mjs')` while still in evaluating state. The dynamic import never resolved, causing the await to hang silently.\n     - **Fix**: Refactored CLI to wrap async logic in a separate `runCli()` async function called from a synchronous `if` block with `.catch()`. Also used `new URL('./rml-repl.mjs', import.meta.url).href` for cwd-independent path resolution.\n     - Verified: `echo \":quit\" | node src/rml-links.mjs repl` exits 0 with proper REPL banner.\n\n5. Problem Solving:\n   - Solved ESM circular import issue by changing from top-level await to wrapped async function\n   - Solved cwd-dependent dynamic import path by using `import.meta.url` URL resolution\n   - Designed `Env` instance pass-through for `evaluate()` to enable persistent state\n   - Both implementations parallel each other: similar API surface (`Repl`, `feed`, meta-commands, completion)\n\n6. All user messages:\n   - Initial message: \"Issue to solve: https://github.com/link-foundation/relative-meta-logic/issues/29 / Your prepared branch: issue-29-9fcddd60fd98 / Your prepared working directory: /tmp/gh-issue-solver-1777477811289 / Your prepared Pull Request: https://github.com/link-foundation/relative-meta-logic/pull/100 / Proceed.\"\n   - Multiple system-reminder messages about TaskCreate/TaskUpdate (gentle reminders, not direct instructions)\n   - System messages confirming tool loads (\"Tool loaded.\")\n\n7. Pending Tasks:\n   - **Task #4 (in_progress)**: Implement Rust REPL `rml repl` subcommand — `rust/src/repl.rs` is created but NOT yet declared as module in `lib.rs` (need `pub mod repl;`) and `main.rs` doesn't handle `repl` argument yet\n   - **Task #5 (pending)**: Add JS and Rust integration tests for REPL (`js/tests/repl.test.mjs` and `rust/tests/repl_tests.rs`)\n   - **Task #6 (pending)**: Update PR 100 description with implementation details\n\n8. Current Work:\n   Just finished writing `/tmp/gh-issue-solver-1777477811289/rust/src/repl.rs` with the `Repl` struct, `ReplStep`, `format_env()`, `run_repl()` driver, and 7 inline unit tests. The module file is complete but is NOT yet linked into the crate — `rust/src/lib.rs` does not yet have `pub mod repl;` declaration, and `rust/src/main.rs` still only handles file-mode (no `repl` subcommand handling). Need to:\n   1. Add `pub mod repl;` to `rust/src/lib.rs`\n   2. Add `use rml::repl::run_repl;` and subcommand dispatch to `rust/src/main.rs`\n   3. Verify with `cargo test` and manual `cargo run -- repl`\n   \n   Most recent file edits include the `evaluate_with_env` refactor in `rust/src/lib.rs` and the new `rust/src/repl.rs`. The build passed: `cargo build` succeeded after the lib.rs refactor.\n\n9. Optional Next Step:\n   Continue with Task #4 (Implement Rust REPL `rml repl` subcommand) — specifically:\n   1. Add `pub mod repl;` declaration to `rust/src/lib.rs` so the new repl module is exposed\n   2. Modify `rust/src/main.rs` to detect `repl` argument and call `rml::repl::run_repl()` with stdin/stdout/stderr (using `io::stdin().lock()`, `io::stdout().lock()`, `io::stderr().lock()`)\n   3. Run `cargo build` and `cargo test` to verify the Rust unit tests in `repl.rs` pass\n   4. Manually verify `echo \":quit\" | cargo run -- repl` works\n   \n   Then proceed to Task #5 (add JS test file `js/tests/repl.test.mjs` and Rust integration test file `rust/tests/repl_tests.rs`) covering state preservation, all meta-commands, and tab-completion. Finally, Task #6 (update PR #100 description with the REPL implementation details, examples, and test coverage).\n\nIf you need specific details from before compaction (like exact code snippets, error messages, or content you generated), read the full transcript at: /home/box/.claude/projects/-tmp-gh-issue-solver-1777477811289/7f4839d3-747e-426e-b5bb-f80f504e2728.jsonl\nContinue the conversation from where it left off without asking the user any further questions. Resume directly — do not acknowledge the summary, do not recap what was happening, do not preface with \"I'll continue\" or similar. Pick up the last task as if the break never happened."
